07392nam a22009495i 9786155053061DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222010hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2018965868  a97861550530617 a10.1515/97861550530612doi  a(DE-B1597)633258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aPOL0050002bisacsh00aPromises of 1968 :bCrisis, Illusion and Utopia /ced. by Vladimir Tismaneanu. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (460 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Picking Up the Pieces: 1968 between Memory and Theory -- tRevolutions and Revolutionaries, Lessons of the Years of Crises -- t1968 in Poland -- tIn Search of a New Left -- tRethinking the Political Scientifically -- tWhat Did They Think They Were Doing? -- tThinking Politically -- tThe Divided Spirit of the Sixties -- tPart Two. Lessons and Legacies of 1968 -- tThe Year 1968 and Its Results -- tThe Prague Spring 1968 -- tFrom Revisionism to Dissent -- tPost-Marxist Mentality and the Intellectual Challenge to Ideology after 1968 -- tYugoslavia’s 1968 -- t1968 Romania -- tPart Three. 1968 in Pieces: Case Studies of Transformation -- tBetrayed Promises -- tThe Kremlin, the Prague Spring, and the Brezhnev Doctrine -- t1968 and the Terrorist Aftermath in West Germany -- tThe Prague Spring -- t“Don’t Push Us, Comrade!” -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is a state of the art reassessment of the significance and consequences of the events associated with the year 1968 in Europe and in North America. Since 1998, there hasn't been any collective, comparative and interdisciplinary effort to discuss 1968 in the light of both contemporary headways of scholarship and new evidence on this historical period. A significant departure from earlier approaches lies in the fact that the manuscript is constructed in unitary fashion, as it goes beyond the East–West divide, trying to identify the common features of the sixties. The latter are analyzed as simultaneously global and local developments. The main problems addressed by the contributors of this volume are: the sixties as a generational clash; the redefinition of the political as a consequence of the ideological challenges posed to the status-quo by the sixty-eighters; the role of Utopia and the de-radicalization of intellectuals; the challenges to imperialism (Soviet/American); the cultural revolution of the sixties; the crisis of 'really existing socialism' and the failure of "socialism with a human face"; the gradual departure from the Yalta-system; the development of a culture of human rights and the project of a global civil society; the situation of 1968 within the general evolution of European history (esp. the relationship of 1968 with 1989). In contrast to existing books, it provides a fundamental and unique synthesis of approaches on 1968: first, it contains critical (vs. nostalgic) re-evaluations of the events from the part of significant sixty-eighters; second, it includes historical analyses based on new archival research; third, it gathers important theoretical re-assessments of the intellectual history of the 1968; and fourth, it bridges 1968 with its aftermath and its pre-history, thus avoiding an over-contextualization of the topics in question.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEuropa. 0aGeschichte. 0aKalter Krieg. 0aMenschenrecht. 0aNordamerika. 0aRevolution. 0aUtopie. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  a1968, Cold War, Ideology, Political philos